Europe
------
[1] UK (North East)
Date: Mon 8 Apr 2013
Source: Sky TV News [abridged & edited]
http://tyneandwear.sky.com/news/article/62518/health-bosses-warn-teesside-measles-outbreak-could-spread-to


Health bosses have warned that a measles outbreak in Teesside could spread to Tyne and Wear. Cases of measles have been on the rise since a report in the medical journal "The Lancet" linked cases of autism to the measles mumps and rubella (MMR) joint vaccine. The article was discredited, and The Lancet published a retraction, but some parents remain unconvinced and have refused to allow their children to receive the MMR vaccine. As a consequence, the herd immunity needed to protect the British people from measles has dropped, putting the very young, the elderly and infirm at risk of what is a serious and highly infectious virus. An outbreak in Swansea, Wales has seen more than 1000 people -- mainly children -- queue up for MMR vaccinations.

The latest Health Protection Agency figures show that of the 200 confirmed cases of measles in the North East, there was one in Gateshead, 2 in Sunderland, and one in Northumberland. All of the other confirmed cases were in County Durham and Teesside, where people aged between 10 and 19 years were worst affected, making up 39 percent of all cases.

There have been no confirmed cases in Newcastle, North Tyneside or South Tyneside, Julia Waller, immunisation lead for the North East PHE Centre, said. "There is no treatment for measles, but it can be prevented by the MMR vaccine, and 2 doses are required to ensure the best protection. "If anyone is unsure about their immunisation status, they should check with their GP."

During 2012, there were 2016 laboratory confirmed cases of measles, the highest annual total since 1994.

[Byline: Hugh Macknight]

