[2] UK (Sussex)
Date: Mon 8 Apr 2013
Source: The Argus [edited]
http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/10339379.Hospitals_on_track_to_avoid_another_measles_outbreak/


Health bosses are hoping they are on track to avoid a repeat of the measles outbreak that swept across Sussex last year [2012]. There have only been 2 confirmed cases of the disease so far this year [2013] compared to 54 for the same period in 2012. There were 330 confirmed cases of the disease in the county during 2012, although the actual number was believed to be higher because samples are not taken from every patient. Brighton and Hove was the worst affected with 195 people falling ill, while East Sussex had 90 and West Sussex 45.

This year [2013], there have been 2 confirmed cases in West Sussex, while Brighton and Hove and East Sussex are clear so far. The outbreak was blamed on poor take up rates for the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine. Around 95 percent of a community needs to have both doses of the jab in order for it to have an impact, and people are being urged to make sure they and their children are completely up to date. The warning comes as health officials battle to contain an outbreak of measles in Swansea, where up to 600 people have been infected.

